defaultThe universal service is under threatdefault&#xa0;defaultBe in no doubt, the universal service as we know it is under threat. The aff
defaultordable six-days-a-week universal service that is so valued in the UK is expensive to provide. 
defaultIt
default is under threat from competition and would be less secure in the hands of a privatised Royal Mail. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe government claims that the universal service is enshr
defaultined in law, but this only covers 
defaultthe bare minimum
default; many aspects of the universal service are set by Ofcom and could easily be changed. And the government has only committed to leave the law unchanged for the duration of this 
defaultP
defaultarliament. In 
defaultless than
default two y
defaultears the government’s commitment runs out.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe legal minimum requirements of the universal service are for one collection and delivery of letters Monday to Saturday and one collection and delivery of packets every Monday to Friday at 
defaulta uniform and
default afforda
defaultble tariff.
default Almost
default 
defaulta
defaultll other aspects are open to change by Ofcom and do not require the agreement of Parliament. This means there is significant scope for the USO to be reduced while still remaining legally compliant; for example, as long as there is one p
defaultroduct (this could be a service slower than Second Class mail) priced at an affordable uniform tariff and that daily collections and deliveries continue, the legal requirements of the USO would be met. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe regulator has recently consulted on user needs f
defaultrom the universal service. It looked at ways the universal service could be changed to make it cheaper to run. These included getting rid of First Class mail (and therefore the next-day service), reducing quality of service standards and cutting delivery d
defaulta
defaultys from six to five a week. 
default&#xa0;
defaultDowngrading the universal service in such a way would disproportionately affect consumers in rural and hard
default-to-
defaultreach areas. Services outside the universal service would not be commercially justifiable and would either become 
defaultvery expensive or not be sustained. Equally if quality of service targets were loosened or removed for what remained of the universal service, this would disproportionately affect certain geographical areas
default;
default if fewer 
defaultletters are required to get to their destination within a certain time, it will inevitably be harder-to-reach locations that are affected.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn its recent review of user needs, Ofcom considered what would happen if quality of service standards for
default first class mail were reduced from the current 93% to 85% (the effect of removing Royal Mail’s air network) and said the following:
default&#xa0;
default“Removing the air network would primarily affect long distance mail, while local mail could continue to receive a high qua
defaultlity next-day service. As such, it would have a disproportionate impact on some parts of the country. While many areas in central England would still receive a service where over 90% of letters are delivered the next day, Scotland, Northern Ireland, South 
defaultWales and more parts of England could see First Class quality of service fall to just 50 to 75%.”
default&#xa0;
defaultThe regulator recently stepped back from recommending any changes – possibly due to their politically sensitive nature – but it is very likely that we will see these issues revisited in the near future. A privately owned Royal Mail, under pressure to gener
defaultate a return for shareholders, 
defaultwill want
default to cut the burden of the universal service and
default will
default lobby for such changes.
default The
default privately 
defaultrun Post NL in the Netherlands has put pressure on both the regulator and the government regarding their univer
defaultsal service ob
defaultligations
default with the result that there are now plans to drop Monday deliveries.
default&#xa0;
defaultCutting pensions to boost privatizationdefault&#xa0;
defaultIn a further 
defaultmove to prepare Royal Mail for sale, the company is 
defaultproposing
default to 
defaultmake 
defaultnew
default 
defaultcut
defaults to
default 
defaultmembers’ 
defaultpension benefits. Following the
default transfer of the majority of the assets and liabilities in the Royal Mail Pension Plan (RMPP) to government last year, a smaller scheme was left with Royal Mail with £2bn in assets to fund future benefit accrual. Now, just one year later, the company is ar
defaultguing that the cost of funding the scheme is higher than it anticipated and plans to cut the final salary link for pensionable service up to April 200
default8. 
defaultInstead 
defaultof
default increasing pension payments to meet its obligations it intends to use the assets left in the
default scheme to 
defaultsubsidise
default its pension contributions rather than paying for the salary link for which 
defaultthe funds were
default intended.
