defaultCompetition in deliveries default&#xa0;defaultThe 
defaultCWU is challenging the model of competition in the postal market. 
defaultThe union wants
default to see a healthy postal market but 
defaultdoes
default not want to see competition at the expense of decent jobs.
default&#xa0;defaultRoyal Mail’s business model is now under threat from TNT’s entry into the 
defaultdirect delivery (end-to-end) market. TNT has se
defaultt up a delivery service in west, 
defaultcentral
default and now south west
default London
default.
default It is 
defaultable to win business because it can choose where, when and what to deliver, without any quality of service or performance standards and
default by undercutting the jobs, pay and conditions of postal workers across the UK.
default 
defaultThis model of competition means
default cherry picking the most profitable parts of Royal Mail’s business and
default cutting costs at the expense of decent jobs. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTNT employs workers on “zero
default-hours” contracts
default, which mean
default workers are not guaranteed any hours. One journalist who went undercover in a TNT depot reports how workers are forced to “hustle” each day to get a day’s work. Bosses over-hire staff to ensure that there will be more than eno
defaultugh people available for a shift, meaning 
defaultworkers get
default turned away. Workers never know whether they will get enough hours a week to make ends meet. Pay is only £7.10 ph in London, £1.45ph below the living wage.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultOfcom has stated that it is monitoring TNT’
defaults entry into the postal delivery market, but despite having powers to act conferred through the Postal Services Act 2011, it is choosing not to regulate to prevent TNT from cherry picking.
default&#xa0;
defaultRoyal Mail workers have voted overwhelmingly in favour of a boycot
defaultt of competitors’ mail in protest at the effect of competition on Royal Mail’s future ability to provide the universal service and
default in protest against
default a competitive model which is predicated on 
defaultlow
default wages and 
defaultpoor 
defaultterms and conditions across the postal indus
defaulttry.
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is defaultan alternativedefault: A new model for Royal Maildefault&#xa0;defaultThere is a positive future for a strong Royal Mail which properly engages its employees. This will only happen through an approach to business operations which reflects 
defaultstrong values of public serv
defaultice
default and 
defaultwhich empowers
default employees to have a 
defaultgenuine
default say in the running of the company.
default&#xa0;
defaultSmall but important changes in the way Royal Mail operates can bring a strong sense of purpose to the company.
default 
defaultA new business model for Royal Mail should set out in clear terms the vision, values and operating model of the 
defaultbusiness
default, through a
default legally binding charter. This should include a
default commitment to public service, social obliga
defaulttions and the universal service.
default I
defaultt 
defaultsh
defaultould establish Royal Mail as a not-for-dividend
default company
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultA charter
default for Royal Mail
default should incorporate a new system of governance which ensure
defaults
default employees, customers and the public have a meaningful sa
defaulty in the way the company is run,
default 
defaultprovid
defaulting
default Royal Mail
default with the independence and the freedom from political interference to which the government aspires. 
default&#xa0;
defaultRoyal Mail’s results for 2012/13 show that it can raise investment capital through its own profits; this is a step towards becoming a self-financing, not-for-dividend company. Without changing ownership, Royal Mail could borrow from money markets, at a che
defaultaper rate, in line with companies like Network Rail. Such methods of investment operate throughout the 
defaultEU for government related entities such as Royal Mail.
